{"_id":"yvpl2d8YMcuo4QPr","name":"Chant","content":"<h1>Chant</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<i>Clerical Conjuration/Summoning</i>\n\t\t\t\t\t</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<table>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tbody><tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Level:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Cleric 2</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Range:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>0</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Duration:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Indefinite (duration of chant)</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Area of Effect:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>30-ft radius centred on caster</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Components:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>V,S</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Casting Time:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>1 turn</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Saving Throw:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>None</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t</tbody></table>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\tChant\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>Once the spell is cast, the cleric must maintain a sonorous chanting of holy words and prayers, which not only lend divine favour to the cleric and his or her allies but also bring disfavour to their foes. <b>For so long as the cleric remains stationary and continues to chant, his or her allies (within the area of effect) gain a bonus of +1 to all attack rolls, damage rolls, and saving throws. Enemies within the spell's area of effect also suffer a -1 to all such die rolls </b>. If the cleric sustains damage, is grappled, or is in some way silenced, the effect of the spell will end.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"I0IQ9ef7ZhLd66iw":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"hash":"91a9b15f18239829f8806045d3870268c25c45c1","sourceId":"JournalEntry.yvpl2d8YMcuo4QPr"},"cf":{"id":"temp_65r8ksx2p43","path":"OSRIC-PC#/CF_SEP/Chapter 2: Spells#/CF_SEP/Cleric Spells","color":"#000000","sort":44}}}
{"_id":"z7Pxx5vvXVyXplps","name":"Adapter's Notes for Fantasy Grounds","content":"<p>This module builds on and fleshes out other OSRIC adaption work for Fantasy Grounds (FG) originally completed by Sterno and Alterzwerg for the FG 2E ruleset; thank you, gentlemen, for your foundational efforts.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>Unlike the referenced works, this module is optimized for use with Celestian's 1E extension to the 2E ruleset; so as to use OSRIC in the closest available FG environment to its inherent structure. It will also work fine without use of the 1E extension, so long as the user is aware of certain changes which substitute OSRIC data in categories where OSRIC and 2E conflict (e.g., all monsters/NPCs default surprise value is lowered to \"2\" from the previous \"3\"; weapon speed values are removed to simple text in the properties line and no longer modify initiative rolls (although high dex for ranged weapons, or other OSRIC initiative modifers, may be placed in that field which will then modify initiative for that action - see notes on initiative below), there is no initiative modifier for size, or casting time modifier for at-will spell abilities, etc., etc., etc.).</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>IMPORTANT: many of OSRIC's ambiguities and omissions are purposeful, so as to sustain long-standing GM interpretations of previous imprecise language and also to avoid possible non-compliance with the OGL or general copyright law in some few areas. If you're aware of some specific variance or additional information in other generally similar rule books, and want that reflected in your copy of the FG OSRIC mod, drag-copy entries (so that FG Forge updates don't override the entry back to \"factory settings\") and make your own modifications to the copied entry, using it in play instead. <i>For example, </i>in my personal campaign I modify the assassination skill values and give ghast stench penalties a duration.</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<h1>Notable (but non-exhaustive) changes and additions</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>The largest change is the inclusion of the text as a reference, along with creation of many tables and modifiers found therein.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>You can use group initiative for speed and combat flow; anyone that has an initiative modifier based on their action should roll individual initiative instead, which will override the group initiative result for that character only. Common actions having initiative modifiers include (but are not limited to) casting spells, using certain magic items, and ranged attacks by high-dex characters. Look at the yellow initiative box associated with that action. If the number inside is <b><u>not </u></b>\"0\" then anyone taking that action should roll individual initiative. This still, in practice, means the group initiative die roll result will be used by nearly everyone most of the time if the GM chooses to use group initiative generally.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Dexterity modifiers to initiative for ranged attacks must be added to the ranged weapon's Weapon Speed field as discussed above. This is accomplished by clicking the black gear in the \"Weapons\" tab for that item and inputting the bonus/penalty into the weapon speed field there. In OSRIC weapon speed doesn't routinely modify initiative so the box normally defaults to \"0\". Example: a character with a long bow has a dex of 17, so the player inputs \"-2\" in the weapon speed field for his longbow item. The yellow \"initiative\" box for the long bow attack would now show as \"-2\" on that character's <i>Actions </i>tab, and rolling invidual initiative by clicking this box when shooting their bow will apply the modifier. [ <b><i>FG Note: </i></b><i>book-OSRIC's initiative system is \"roll high\"; FG's built-in system is \"roll low\". So what shows in OSRIC as a \"+2\" modifier becomes a \"-2\" in FG (or vice-versa for penlties) - the point is the modifier is beneficial (or detrimental) to the character </i>]</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>As mentioned above, surprise values are updated to OSRIC's default value of 2 or less; weapon speeds are removed from items except as data in the property field, and no longer adjust initiative roll results</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Dwarf/Gnome Abilities: These detection abilities are added as skills; players will need to drag them on to their character sheets.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Auto-updating skills: Assassins' and thieves' various skills now automatically increase upon a new level; however, this wipes out modifications previously entered for race and/or dexterity (which will require re-entry). However, on balance, this lessens effort by a greater degree than it increases it as not all characters will have these bonuses.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Unarmed combat attacks of pummeling, grappling, and overbearing are given as weapon-items. These should be dragged to the characters inventory just as when taking dagger, mace or sword as weapons for that character. However, they populate on the powers tab instead of the attacks tab, as some of them have follow on special effects such as \"restrained\" or \"prone\". Go to the powers tab to use the unarmed attack forms and roll from there.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>MU and Clerical \"Spheres\": Spells for clerics and MUs are now also given \"spheres\": clerical and MU, respectively. This is a mechanical/database convenience, only, so as to make it possible to bring up only their spell lists without admixture of druids' or illusionists' spells. In OSRIC proper there are no spheres.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Item Saves: For those GMs desiring incorporation of item saving throws, the roll-under skill function is experimentally repurposed as item saves. The saves are inverted (a roll-over save value of \"13\" is changed to a roll-under \"8\"), and a player may drag item save categories a GM wishes to make expeditiously available to their character sheet as \"nonweapon/skills\" - they have no functionality unless dragged on to a character sheet. This allows the quick function of clicking through the list if item destruction is possible, at the admitted expense of a possibly lengthy list in the character sheet itself. However, not all the save categories must be used (this GM ignores any where the math makes a given result nearly inevitable).</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Morale values are updated to percentile scores</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>XP values are given for all entries - no more \"variable\" entries that mean you have to figure it out using tables! NOTE: XP values provided for variant monsters and classed NPCs are my own calculations using my judgement to interpret the OSRIC XP determination tables. You may feel they are too high (or too low). Don't hesitate to replace them if you prefer.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>the \"ammo\" category is used for items such as arrows and bullets; \"weapon\" is reserved for persistent items.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>How GMs handle magic armour weight varies considerably; in these modules magic armour weight and base move isn't modified from the non-magical version's. Each GM can choose whether to reduce weight of a magic armour item by half (or entirely), give a magical suit of plate mail a move rate of 12 or 9, etc.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>In OSRIC, attacks that multiply damage: backstab, certain swords against giants and dragons, etc., multiply only the base damage rolled by the weapon and not strength or magic bonuses. Existing automation available multiples all of these bonuses together with the base damage roll, and so isn't used. Manual modifications of the damage must be made by reapplying the bonus after reviewing the base damage rolled in the chat window.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li>Many OSRIC magic items are usable \"1/week\", or some other value not otherwise available in FG. In these cases they will show \"X\"/day to establish they are not \"use at-will\" items, with the true intermittency listed in the text.</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t<h1>The Inclusion of Spell (and Item) NPCs</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>The employment of many spells or items result in combat entities that aren't existing monsters, and are largely independent of the caster; an example is a phantasmal killer. Certain \"Spell/Item NPCs\" are added to the set for convenience in accounting for these entities on the field of battle. In general, an NPC was created if:</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>1. The effect is not enhancing a caster ability</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>2. It isn't replicating an existing monster</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>3. It operates independently of the caster</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>4. it has different characteristics - for example, the phantasmal killer always attacks as a 4HD monster, which may vary from the attack rating of the caster.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"I0IQ9ef7ZhLd66iw":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"hash":"7fb88c7c3c187bf5b15e6ce648ad26c8fbbf67b0","sourceId":"JournalEntry.z7Pxx5vvXVyXplps"},"cf":{"id":"temp_ybu106or2z","path":"OSRIC-PC#/CF_SEP/OSRIC#/CF_SEP/Adapter's Notes for Fantasy Grounds","color":"#000000","sort":5}}}
{"_id":"zFS8kxAjBkNewx9T","name":"Find Traps","content":"<h1>Find Traps</h1>\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<i>Clerical Divination</i>\n\t\t\t\t\t</p>\n\t\t\t\t\t<table>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tbody><tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Level:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Cleric 2</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Range:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>30-ft</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Duration:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>3 turns</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Area of Effect:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>10-ft wide path</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Components:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>V,S</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Casting Time:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>5 segments</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>Saving Throw:</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<td>None</td>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\n\t\t\t\t\t</tbody></table>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\tFind Traps\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t<p>This spell permits the cleric to discern the existence of traps, both of magical and mechanical nature. The cleric must be looking at a trap in order to perceive it.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"I0IQ9ef7ZhLd66iw":3},"flags":{"scene-packer":{"hash":"fe51818ac72e804e09be8321b3c0aaf782125982","sourceId":"JournalEntry.zFS8kxAjBkNewx9T"},"cf":{"id":"temp_65r8ksx2p43","path":"OSRIC-PC#/CF_SEP/Chapter 2: Spells#/CF_SEP/Cleric Spells","color":"#000000","sort":68}}}
